you'll see how R played a pivotal role in the success of this project.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:13.000
So Ian, to move a simple robotic arm, what do we actually need?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Yeah, to move a simple robotic arm, the first thing that you need to do is actually

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
set up your robotic arm, which basically means setting up the hardware that you're going to be using.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And the beauty about this is that the pieces already come, you know, pre-cut.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:31.000
All you have to do is actually remove the pieces and actually assemble them together.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And once you do this, it only takes about 30 minutes to an hour.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
And with the right enthusiasm, you can actually do this.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:43.000
And you're already done with the first step, which is actually setting up the manipulator.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So after you're done with the setup, after you're done with the hardware,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:54.000
you proceed to ask the next logical question becomes, what are the manipulator inputs?

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And just as a disclaimer, in the course of this talk, I will be using the term manipulator

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
and robotic arm to mean one and the same thing. So don't get lost in that.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:09.000
So we realized from the video that Eric just showed us that our manipulator used voice as an input.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So how did we achieve this in R?

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So the first thing that we did was actually record the voice using audio package in R,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
whereby we recorded the command B2 and G2.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Once we have our voice input, we transcribed this using Azure, Azure Cognitive Services,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:31.000
and transcribed the voice input into text using HDR package and JSON Lite package.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.000
I'm sure some of you are familiar with that.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
After doing that, the transcription and getting the output,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
we proceeded next to do some assertions to ensure that indeed the format,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
that result that we got from Azure is actually correct,

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
because you realize in some cases there are some errors.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
And after doing this, we extracted the characters from the text,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
whereby B2 was the initial position and G2 was the final position.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:05:00.000
So to make the API call to Azure, we used the sample code shown in the slide,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
whereby all we needed to do is actually define our subscription key,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.000
which we actually got from Azure once we set up our cognitive services on the platform,

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
define the context type, which was audio file,

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
the flavor of English that we were using, which was US English,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:22.000
upload our recorded audio, got the transcribed data using post request to the API.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And then from this, we actually pulled the initial position

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
and the final position in text format.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
So just to recap, what's the state of data at this point?

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So at this point, we had our voice input, B2 and G2,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
ran it through Azure, and then we got a string equivalent,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:46.000
a string which is B2 and G2 representing a specific chess box actually,

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
which is B2 and G2, which is the final position.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:56.000
So after deriving the string, the next bit becomes defining the workspace

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
whereby the manipulator will be working on.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And to answer this, we ask ourselves the question,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
where is the manipulator actually going?

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
And I believe, Eric, you're going to tell us where was the manipulator going?

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
To answer your question, Ian, what we need to do is to assign a special coordinate

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
to the chessboard location that we just obtained from the transcription.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
So how did we approach this?

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:25.000
So we first started by creating a virtual board in R using ggplot.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.000
Probably a lot of you have used it to create some elegant graphics in R.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.000
Once we did this, we extracted the central pixel location.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And then the next point was translating the pixel location

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
to actual real-world board coordinates in centimeters.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
And to do this, we used the scales package in R.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
So why did we use this approach?

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So we figured out that different boards come in different flavors and dimensions.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
So we needed a virtual board that is static.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And then depending on the dimensions of the chessboard,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:02.000
one can then translate the pixel location to actual real-world location

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:06.000
depending on the dimensions of his or her board.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.000
So at this point, we can combine everything and put it in a good old table

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:17.000
where we have the position of the square box on the chessboard.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
And most importantly, the x and y coordinates in centimeters

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
that would represent a location of a chess piece on a chessboard.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
So let's wrap this up.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So we started with speech and then we got a transcription.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
And then for each start and end point,

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:38.000
we now have x, y, and z coordinates

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
that represent the position of a chess piece on a chessboard.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
So for instance, B2 can be represented by 6 centimeter on the x,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
15 centimeter on the y, and 3.5 on the z.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.000
So 3.5 is just the height of the chess piece

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
that will be moving around on the chessboard.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
So the next logical question now becomes,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:01.000
how will the manipulator get there?

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Yeah, so to answer this question,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
you just take a moment and just observe the video that's playing.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:11.000
And you realize from the video that these three blue things

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.000
that have some cables connected to them,

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:14.000
those are actually motors,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
and they are responsible for the manipulator motion.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And in this case, we had three motors which were controlling motion.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And yeah, and you realize with a motor,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
the motion of a motor is actually rotational in nature.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
And from Eric's point,

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
we now have our coordinates in terms of x, y, and z.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
So we have to find a way of linking the x, y, z and the motor angles.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Converting x, y, z coordinates into the equivalent motor angles.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And to do this, we use a branch of math called inverse kinematics.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
I know it's a mouthful, but just bear with us for a second.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Yeah.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
So at the moment, let's treat inverse kinematics as a black box.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
So what inverse kinematics does in a nutshell is,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
it takes x, y, z inputs,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
converts them into the equivalent angles.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
Therefore, we have our x, y, z coordinates,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
which are actually converted into motor angles

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:06.000
that can now move the manipulator.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
And just to give you a feel of what inverse kinematics is all about,

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:11.000
I give you some fair warning.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:12.000
There's some math ahead.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So just hold on tight and just bear with us.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.000
And yeah.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
So to do inverse kinematics,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:23.000
it's actually based on trigonometry functions,

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
which are the things that most of us learned in elementary

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
and just need to brush up a little bit on.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.000
Yeah.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And the beauty about this is that most robotic arms,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:33.000
once you buy the kit,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.000
it comes with the instructions to inverse kinematics.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
Most probably people, there are people,

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
there are ripples out there whereby people have already done the inverse

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
kinematics, so you don't really have to know, you know,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
the deep stuff about these things.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
So you just need a high level overview and just use the code that is

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
being used by other people.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Yeah.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:55.000
And in case it's not there, in case it's not provided,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
you can actually come up with your own.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And this is a sample of what we actually did.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And as you can see, we use the basic, you know,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:06.000
tangent sine and cosine functions that, you know,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
we learned in elementary.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
So all you need to do is actually, is actually, you know,

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
brush up on those skills.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.000
And then, yeah,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
we'll probably give a more detailed approach as to how we came up with

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
these equations in our repo.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:21.000
Yeah.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
So just to recap, what's the state of data at this point?

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
So at this point we got our audio file, which was the input.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
We transcribed it and got the string B2 and G2.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:35.000
We actually transposed the B2 and G2 into the real world XYZ

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
coordinates that represented, you know,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
chess piece locations of the chess board.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.000
And using inverse kinematics,

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
we're able now to translate the XYZ into the equivalent motor

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:46.000
angles.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
And you realize that since we have three motors,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
the way we identify which is which motor is actually by using the

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:53.000
string.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
So A, letter A corresponded to the first motor,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
letter B to the second motor, letter C to the third motor.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:03.000
So 112 A meant 112 degrees to motor A,

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.000
126 B meant 126 degrees to motor B,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
107 C meant 107 C,

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
107 degrees to motor C.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
And finally we go to the fun part,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
which is actually moving the robotic arm.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So Eric,

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
how did you move the manipulator to the desired positions?

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
So let's answer Ian's question.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.000
At this point,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
we have everything that we need to move the chess pieces on the chess

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.000
board.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
So you know the location of the chess piece,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
and you know the angles required to move the manipulator to that

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:35.000
position.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:40.000
So we now need to find a way of linking R and the manipulator and

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:41.000
how to do this.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So this is the architecture that we used,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
where R is doing all the heavy lifting and finally sending a string of

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
data that Ian just described.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And at the middle,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
we have an electrode device known as a microcontroller.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:53.000
And a microcontroller,

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.000
you can think of it as an electrical device where you can connect

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:57.000
multiple peripherals,

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
such as motors or LEDs or speakers or sensors,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:08.000
then define some instructions on how to send electrical signals to

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:11.000
manipulate those peripherals that are connected to it.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.000
In our case,

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.000
these are motors.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
We want the motors to rotate to some given angles.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
So that was the work of the microcontroller,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:20.000
which in our case was Arduino,

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
to just receive a string of data and then send a signal to each

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
respective motor.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
And then the motors would rotate and bring the manipulator to the

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
desired position.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
So once we had this figured out,

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:36.000
the next logical thing was now to ask ourselves,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:42.000
how do we send data from R to the microcontroller?

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:47.000
At this point is when we realized that most microcontrollers can

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
be programmed via a serial interface.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
So a serial interface is a communication interface in which data can

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
be sent and received sequentially.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
So with this,

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.000
we just had figured out how to set up a serial interface in R.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.000
And then a microcontroller can read that serial interface and send

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:14.000
an electrical signal to move our motors and bring the manipulator to

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:15.000
the desired position.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So how do we set up a serial interface in R?

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
Surprisingly enough,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
there's already a packet that helps us do this.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
So the packet is known as packet serial.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
So with serial,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
the serial packet just requires a few parameters to set up the serial

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.000
interface.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And some of these parameters,

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
important arguments rather is the port number.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So this is the USB port,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.000
which you connect the microcontroller to your PC.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:51.000
The next argument is the baud rate.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
So this is the rate at which you send and receive data,

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
which was 9,600 bits per second.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.000
So you want a speed that is just right,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
not too fast and not too slow.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And the next parameters are there by default,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
and they just help in structuring how data is sent to the serial

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.000
interface.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
For instance, do you want a new line appended at each instance of

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:16.000
the data?

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:17.000
Yes.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
What character do you want to append after each new line current

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:22.000
return?

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
So this just describes how to structure data that is sent to the

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.000
serial interface.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
And after you've done how to set up the serial interface,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
you now write data to it.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And to write data to it,

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:41.000
we just combined the strings of angles into a vector.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Then we use path work to write each element of the vector to the

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
serial connection.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.000
So once the data is on a serial connection,

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:56.000
now it's time for the microcontroller to read that data and do its

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:57.000
thing.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
So these are the instructions that we put on the microcontroller

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:05.000
whereby it checks whether data is available on the serial,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
reads data from the serial,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
passes integers to extract the numeric part of the string.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.000
And then depending on the case, say A, B, or C,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:24.000
it writes that value or that integer to the respective motor

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
associated with a string.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.000
For instance, if it sees A, it knows I'm sending an angle to motor

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
A. B sends an angle to motor B.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:41.000
And at this point, we have achieved the basis of our whole project.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:47.000
We started from transcribing data all the way to knowing the

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
angles to which to move our robotic arm.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
And finally, moving our robotic arm using the help of a

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:54.000
microcontroller.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:57.000
So with this, you can set up some,

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
I would say some more complex tasks,

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:07.000
such as achieving a capture move using our manipulator,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
like we're going to see in the following clip.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
G3 and B2 capture.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:22.000
Perfect.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
So this is basically using all that information that we have,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:27.000
you know, that we have described,

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
and just adding some layers of complexity to it.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And at this point,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:35.000
we hope you have successfully showed you some touch of our

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:36.000
robotics.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:40.000
So everything has some pros and cons, right Ian?

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
Yeah, definitely.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Everything has its own pros and cons.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
And in the course of this project,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
we realized that there are some key areas that we wanted to

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
highlight that are really excelled.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
And one of the key areas that we saw that are excelled was when

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:55.000
it came to data manipulation,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:59.000
it was easier to do data manipulation with R because I realized

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
that R is actually optimized for such tasks.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:05.000
And also we realized in the course of the project that a big

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:09.000
chunk of robotics is actually a data problem and it can also

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
easily be solved in R.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
Therefore it became quite easy using R.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:18.000
And also R is actually less computationally expensive as compared

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
to what we've used before,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
which was MATLAB.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
It's a software that actually is used by guys in our field,

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
specifically the guys doing research.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And the reason why we say this is because we realized with

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
MATLAB, once you boot it up,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
it loads all the packages that come with MATLAB.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
But we realized with R, you only load the packages that you need.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
Therefore it becomes a bit light on the PC and it becomes easier

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:44.000
to use.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And also R is open source,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:50.000
therefore meaning anybody can actually reproduce what you did once

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
they have access to the R.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And actually it becomes easier to actually do this without having

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
so much of resources.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So the main issues that we faced when using R was that the

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:07.000
serial communication, which Eric just highlighted,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:08.000
was a bit slower.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Yeah, and we thought that maybe this could be an issue with the

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
package and it's something that we are willing to look at in

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
future and maybe offer some suggestions.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
And also the audio package that we used to record audio was a

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
bit, it wasn't up to date because each and every time after

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:28.000
recording an audio object,

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:31.000
we had to restart R so that you can actually record another

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:35.000
audio object, meaning you can't do two consecutive inputs

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:38.000
without first necessarily having to restart R,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:42.000
which was a bit annoying and, you know, it was a bit hectic.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
So what's next?

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
Because, you know, like, what's next?

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Which is our next adventure?

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:53.000
So currently we plan on adding and contributing R packages,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
specifically packages geared towards the engineering field,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
because we believe that given our background,

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.000
this is something that we can actually, you know,

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
add to the community and actually build the community.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
And also speaking about communities,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:10.000
we also want to build R communities specifically in engineering,

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:13.000
such as what we have in, you know, medicine, R in pharma.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:18.000
We want also to have a community of R users that are actually in

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.000
the engineering field.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And also because we are adventurous,

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
we hope that we'll explore the unexpected uses of R.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
And once we are able to get something,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
we'll share with everyone.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.000
Yeah.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And Eric, I don't know if there's anything else that I left out.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Not much, Ian.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
Everything was really well said.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
And thanks a lot for that.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
So hoping that we get to the next adventure soon.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:45.000
So, but anyhow, we really wanted to wrap everything up,

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:49.000
but just noting that a lot of the majority we did,

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:53.000
we did using packages that are already in the R ecosystem.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:55.000
We thought when we were starting this,

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:58.000
actually we had to reinvent some tools,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
but there was no need for that.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
Everything we used was everything that has already been built and we

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
just had to modify it to our needs.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:11.000
So we hope we really present a good case of an unexpected using R.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And mostly we hope that we've inspired one or two to try out,

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:19.000
you know, R in their domain or, you know,

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:22.000
R in some fun activities they have, you know,

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:25.000
just using R everywhere, anywhere.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
So anyhow, time to wrap up.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
So we'd hope to wrap up with, you know,

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:33.000
let's say a quote from Alice in Wonderland,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.000
like we did from at the beginning,

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.000
but we did not find one that's really befitting to our story.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:40.000
So we made one up.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:43.000
So if there's ever a story written about Eric and Ian,

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
we hope it goes like this.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
You know, for you see,

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:50.000
somewhere out of the way things had happened lately that Eric and Ian

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:54.000
began to think that very few things indeed were really impassable and an

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:57.000
emphasis to the R in impassable.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:00.000
So thank you so much for listening to us.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
Please do have a good conference ahead and take care of yourselves.

